text: In June 2018, MedMen looked to become the Apple of pot, the first mainstream, nationwide consumer brand for the product that drove so many Americans to ingest and invest https://t.co/TK6Z6WljEg

name: politico
text: Then, just a few months after its opening, it all began to unravel. The company got hit with a class-action lawsuit from employees alleging labor law violations. Miffed investors sued the founders. https://t.co/TK6Z6WljEg

name: politico
text:
The suit alleged excessive spending on security as well as using company funds on the likes of a custom Tesla SUV, “pearl-white” Cadillac Escalades, and a salary for the CEO's personal marriage counselor.⁣⁣⁣
https://t.co/TK6Z6WljEg https://t.co/SkrOShkmWb

name: politico
text: MedMen's fall reverberates far beyond its stakeholders, because its glitzy rise was propelled by the promise of an entire industry https://t.co/TK6Z6WljEg

name: politico
text: Its woes reflect the precarious status of the cannabis business: legalized by states but still criminalized by the federal government, its position makes traditional bank financing impossible and puts companies at the mercy of a patchwork of regulator https://t.co/TK6Z6WljEg
